In October 2009, President Barack Obama proclaimed National Information Literacy Awareness Month. The proclamation emphasized the importance of being adept at acquiring, collating, and evaluating information in the Information Age. It highlighted the need for citizens to be competent in communication technologies and to know how to navigate the vast amount of information available to them. The proclamation also emphasized the importance of educators and institutions of learning adjusting to the new realities of information management. It called for increasing awareness of information literacy so that citizens can make informed decisions in various aspects of life. The proclamation concluded by urging educational and community institutions to help Americans find and evaluate the information they seek.